******
[1] Minnesota (Goodhue and Wabasha counties)
Date: Wed 19 Nov 2014
Source: KTTC [edited]
http://www.kttc.com/story/27422372/2014/11/18/zumbrota-mazeppa-schools-dealing-with-whooping-cough-outbreak


An outbreak of whooping cough [pertussis] has affected the Zumbrota-Mazeppa Public Schools. At least 11 children in Zumbrota-Mazeppa Middle School and Zumbrota-Mazeppa High School [in Zumbrota, Goodhue County, Minnesota] are confirmed to have the infection. Additionally, 80 children stayed home sick from Zumbrota-Mazeppa schools on Tuesday, 18 Nov 2014, although not all of the cases are related to the outbreak. Doctors and health professionals in the Zumbrota area were still tracking the apparent outbreak of pertussis on Wednesday, 19 Nov 2014. State, county, and local officials compared notes on the outbreak in a conference call.

Mayo Clinic Dr. Elizabeth Cozine said she has been treating confirmed cases in her clinic in Zumbrota. She wants people to know that if you know for sure you have been exposed to pertussis, you should call your doctor. She said you might not need to come to the clinic to be treated.

KTTC talked with the mother of an 8-year-old girl who is one of the 11 confirmed cases of pertussis. "What I did learn about my daughter's pertussis is it acts like the common cold," she said. "You have no idea that it's anything more severe."

The Minnesota Department of Health has taken interest in the outbreak as well. A conference call between the Department of Health and the health departments of Goodhue and Wabasha counties is planned for Wednesday morning, 19 Nov 2014.

The Minnesota Department of Health advises kids to get vaccinated so they can avoid whooping cough and for those suspected of having whooping cough to stay home from school.

[Byline: Taj Simmons]

