[2] Michigan (Grand Traverse County)
Date: Thu 20 Nov 2014
Source: MLive [edited]
http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2014/11/confirming_cases_of_whooping_c.html


The Grand Traverse County [Michigan] Health Department has confirmed 34 cases of pertussis, commonly known as whooping cough, including 12 new cases this week. 27 of the confirmed cases are tied to 2 schools, Grand Traverse Academy, a K-12 charter school, and Traverse City Area Public Schools (TCAPS). Health department officials say they are working closely with affected schools.

"We continue to actively monitor this situation and make adjustments to make sure we have adequate staff," said Mike Lahey, the emergency preparedness coordinator for the health department.

12 of the confirmed cases are associated with Grand Traverse Academy outbreak, up from 11 on Monday, 17 Nov 2014. The school of 1200 students reopened on Monday, 17 Nov 2014, after shutting down on 11 Nov 2014 because spread of the illness.

The health department says there are 166 probable cases linked to the charter school outbreak. Many more are being tested according to physician offices reports. This week Superintendent Susan Dameron, superintendent of Grand Traverse Academy, said all of the students at risk have taken the preventative antibiotic.

There are currently 15 confirmed cases at Traverse City Area Public Schools, up from 7 on Monday, 17 Nov 2014, according to Christine Guitar, director of marketing and communications for TCAPS. "We continue to work in close collaboration with the Grand Traverse County Health Department to identify possible cases and provide information about pertussis to families," said Guitar, who said there are also confirmed cases in other school districts and in neighboring counties.

"It is important that both children and adults are up-to-date on their immunization," the health department reiterated in Thursday's [20 Nov 2014] update. "Booster shots for pertussis are critical because, unlike some other vaccine-preventable diseases, neither the pertussis disease nor vaccine confers lifelong immunity."

[Byline: Monica Scott]

